Additional Production Use Grant

This Additional Production Use Grant permits limited commercial production use
of the Licensed Work, subject to the terms below. These terms define the scope
of the Additional Use Grant and do not limit the non-production rights granted
by this License.

1. Definitions

"Software" means the Licensed Work and all associated source code, components,
and documentation licensed under this License.

"Personal Use" means use of the Software by an individual solely for personal,
educational, evaluation, research, or hobby purposes, and not for commercial
advantage or business operations.

"Permitted Product Use" means use of the Software as an embedded component
within a software application or service provided by you, where the Software
operates as internal execution infrastructure and is not exposed as a standalone
or general-purpose service.

"Execution Service" means any service, platform, API, or offering that enables
third parties to execute workflows, programs, or tasks using functionality
substantially similar to or derived from the Software.

"General-Purpose Platform" means a product or service that allows third parties
to define, configure, or execute arbitrary or broadly scoped workflows,
integrations, or automations across multiple systems or domains, independent of
a primary application domain.

"Competing Service" means any Execution Service or General-Purpose Platform
where the Software constitutes a material part of the functionality offered to
third parties.

"Third Party" means any individual or entity other than you and your Affiliates.

"Affiliate" means any entity that directly or indirectly controls, is controlled
by, or is under common control with you, where "control" means ownership of more
than fifty percent (50%) of the voting interests or the power to direct
management and policies.

2. Permitted Uses

Subject to the terms of this License, you may:

(a) Personal Use

Use, reproduce, modify, and deploy the Software for Personal Use.

(b) Product Use (Commercial Allowed)

Use and deploy the Software as part of a Permitted Product Use, including within
commercial applications or services, provided that:

the Software operates solely as internal execution infrastructure; and

Third Parties do not access or interact with the Software as a standalone or
general-purpose service.

(c) Self-Hosting

Deploy the Software in self-hosted, private cloud, or on-premises environments
for Personal Use or Permitted Product Use.

(d) User Configuration

Allow end users of your product to configure workflows, automations, or
behaviors within your application, provided such functionality remains within
the scope of your application's primary domain and does not expose the Software
as a General-Purpose Platform.

3. Additional Production Use Restrictions

Except as expressly permitted by this Additional Production Use Grant, you may
not, and may not permit any Third Party to:

(a) Competing Services

Offer, operate, or make available a Competing Service.

(b) Execution as a Service

Provide Third Parties with access to the Software as an Execution Service or
General-Purpose Platform.

(c) Standalone Exposure

Expose the Software, directly or indirectly, as a standalone service, API, or
platform whose primary purpose is to execute workflows, automations, or tasks
on behalf of Third Parties.

(d) Platform Use

Use the Software in a manner where it constitutes the primary value or
functionality of a service offered to Third Parties, including where such
service enables those Third Parties to execute or manage workflows or
integrations across multiple systems independent of a primary application
domain.

(e) Resale or Sublicensing

Sublicense, sell, lease, or otherwise commercialize the Software as
infrastructure for Third Parties where the Software forms a material component
of the offering.

4. Clarifying Examples (Non-Exhaustive)

Permitted Uses include:

operating the Software as internal infrastructure across multiple teams;

embedding the Software within a domain-specific product or service;

enabling application-specific automation or workflow configuration by end users;

running the Software in internal or customer-facing systems where it remains an
implementation detail.

Prohibited Uses include:

offering a general-purpose automation or workflow platform powered by the
Software;

exposing a developer-facing API or service that provides execution capabilities
based on the Software;

operating a hosted or multi-tenant service where the Software is the primary
mechanism for third-party workflow execution.

